<h2>What Is Family Therapy?</h2>
<p>Family therapy treats the family as a system rather than treating one member individually. It is grounded in systems theory — the understanding that individuals are embedded in relational systems, and that problems arising in a family are best understood and addressed at the level of the system, not just the individual.</p>

<p>This doesn't mean the family as a whole is pathological or that blame is distributed evenly. It means that the patterns, communication styles, roles, and dynamics operating in the family contribute to and maintain the difficulties presenting — and that changing the system produces change in individuals that individual therapy alone may not achieve.</p>

<h2>When Family Therapy Is Indicated</h2>
<ul>
  <li>A child or adolescent presenting with behavioural or emotional difficulties (where family dynamics are often part of the picture)</li>
  <li>Communication breakdown between parents and adolescent children</li>
  <li>Family conflict that individual therapy hasn't resolved</li>
  <li>Adjusting to a major family change: divorce, bereavement, serious illness, remarriage, new sibling</li>
  <li>Eating disorders (family-based treatment is first-line for adolescent anorexia)</li>
  <li>A family member with addiction, mental illness, or disability affecting the whole system</li>
  <li>Reunification after estrangement or family breakdown</li>
</ul>

<h2>Major Approaches</h2>

<h3>Structural Family Therapy</h3>
<p>Developed by Salvador Minuchin, structural family therapy examines boundaries, hierarchies, and roles within the family. Unhealthy patterns — enmeshment (blurred boundaries), disengagement (too rigid), parentified children, triangulation — are identified and restructured. The therapist actively intervenes to shift the family structure rather than simply facilitating discussion.</p>

<h3>Strategic Family Therapy</h3>
<p>Strategic approaches focus on specific problematic patterns and sequences — the interaction cycles around the identified problem — and intervene directly to disrupt them. They are typically shorter-term and problem-focused.</p>

<h3>Narrative Family Therapy</h3>
<p>Narrative therapy explores the stories families tell about themselves and their members — how problems come to be located in individuals, how certain narratives maintain distress, and how alternative stories can be developed. It is non-pathologising by design.</p>

<h3>Family-Based Treatment (FBT) for Eating Disorders</h3>
<p>FBT (Maudsley Approach) is the most evidence-based treatment for adolescent anorexia nervosa. It enlists parents as the primary agents of recovery in the first phase — externalising the illness and supporting nutritional restoration — before progressively returning control to the adolescent.</p>

<h2>Online Family Therapy</h2>
<p>Online family therapy works when family members can be in the same location together during the session, or can join from different locations (particularly relevant for co-parenting arrangements or families with members in different cities). The therapist manages the online session dynamics as they would in-person.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>One family member won't come. Can we still do family therapy?</strong><br/>
Yes. Working with the willing members of a family system still produces change — people's shifts in the system affect others' positions. It's less comprehensive than whole-family work, but valuable.</p>

<p><strong>Is family therapy instead of or alongside individual therapy?</strong><br/>
Both are common. For a child or adolescent, individual therapy and family therapy often run concurrently. For adults with individual concerns embedded in family dynamics, combining both is often the most effective approach.</p>

